¬ß¬ß Factorization of $A$ from a sequence of reducers ‚¶â
¬∂ ‚¶ä
  ‚Äñ Let $(A ‚àà ùó•^{m √óm}, b ‚àà ùó•^{m})$ be an ordinarily reducible
    linear system. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ The ‚ù¨ordinary reducer sequence‚ù≠ is a sequence of reducer
    matrices $L_{1}, ‚Ä¶ L_{m-1}$ with $A_1 = L_1A$ and $A_i =
    L_iA_{i-1}$ for $2 ‚â§ i ‚â§ m-1$. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ In other words, $U ‚àà ùó•^{m √óm}$ defined by
    <equation id='equation:ordinaryreducerfactorization:main'>
      ‚Äñ U = L_{m-1} ‚ãØ L_2 L_1 A ‚¶â
    </equation>
    is the ordinary row reduction of $A$. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ $U$ is upper triangular. ‚¶â
‚¶â

¬∂ ‚¶ä
  ‚Äñ If $L_{m-1}¬∑s L_2 L_1$ in
    Equation~\eqref{equation:ordinaryreducerfactorization:main} is
    invertible, then we have
    ‚óá ‚¶ä
      ‚Äñ A = \inv{(L_{m-1}¬∑s L_2 L_1)}U, ‚¶â
    ‚¶â
    which is a factorization of $A$. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ Each $L_i$ is invertible, so
    ‚óá ‚¶ä
      ‚Äñ \inv{(L_{m-1} ‚ãØ L_2 L_1)} = \inv{L}_1\inv{L}_2‚ãØ\inv{L}_{m-1}. ‚¶â
    ‚¶â‚¶â

  ‚Äñ So we are interested in the inverse of $L_i$ for $i ‚â§
    m-1$. ‚¶â

